1ï¸âƒ£ Definition

Decorator Pattern is a structural design pattern that allows us to add new behavior or responsibilities to an object dynamically (at runtime) without modifying its original class.

ğŸ‘‰ It follows the principle:
â€œOpen for extension, Closed for modification.â€

2ï¸âƒ£ Why Decorator Pattern Came

Decorator Pattern came to solve problems caused by:

Too many subclasses

Feature explosion

Rigid inheritance hierarchy

Need to add features dynamically

âŒ Problem without Decorator

If we use inheritance for every feature combination:

Coffee
 â”œâ”€â”€ CoffeeWithMilk
 â”œâ”€â”€ CoffeeWithSugar
 â”œâ”€â”€ CoffeeWithMilkAndSugar
 â”œâ”€â”€ CoffeeWithCream
 â”œâ”€â”€ CoffeeWithMilkSugarCream


ğŸ˜µ Too many classes â†’ Class explosion

3ï¸âƒ£ What Problem Decorator Solves

Avoids subclass explosion

Adds functionality without touching existing code

Allows mix & match of features

Supports runtime behavior change

4ï¸âƒ£ When to Use Decorator Pattern

Use Decorator Pattern when:

You want to add optional features

You donâ€™t want to modify existing classes

Inheritance leads to too many subclasses

Behavior should be added at runtime

You want flexible combinations of features

5ï¸âƒ£ When NOT to Use Decorator Pattern

Avoid Decorator when:

Object is very simple

No dynamic behavior is required

Too many decorators make debugging hard

6ï¸âƒ£ Key Components of Decorator Pattern
ğŸ”¹ 1. Component (Interface / Abstract Class)

Defines the base behavior.

ğŸ”¹ 2. Concrete Component

Original object whose behavior we want to extend.

ğŸ”¹ 3. Decorator (Abstract)

Implements the same interface and wraps the component.

ğŸ”¹ 4. Concrete Decorator

Adds extra behavior before or after delegating to the wrapped object.

7ï¸âƒ£ Structure (Logical Flow)
